 @VWCM  I woulds say FSR 4 is already superior. IMO transformer over sharpens everything. I don't really want things in the back ground that were soft in the native presentation on purpose to all of a sudden be super sharp. Or for the AI to invent detail in such areas where none existed. The occlusion garbling DLSS does is also noticeably worse as HUB does point out. If FSR 4 is equally stable, sharp in the foreground and leaves background detail close to native... while not garbling foreground elements when they pass over complex backgrounds. It has won already imo. Transformer only looks better in that its over sharpened. I know a lot of people like the look of sharpened things. Personally I'll take the AMD solution where they are doing a lot of sharpening where it matters and retaining the more artistic presentation with proper Ariel perspective... and soft (on purpose) detail. 

Also think AMD wins if we can just honestly make a sane logical argument for FSR being superior at all. DLSS is not an auto win anymore. Game support will level out. (and gamers that really really really want to can already use 3rd party things to force FSR into DLSS 3.1 games)

On the RT performance. I don't know more and more reviewers and gamers are starting to notice the 1% low issues. Is the 9070XT slightly slower then both the 5070 and 5080. Yes sure the averages are lower. Yet somehow the 1% lows of the 9070xt are better in many titles then even the 5080. Its a better gaming experience even if its playing a game at 120FPS instead of 140. Its crazy that the 9070 is doing 120-100 FPS vs 140-80. The result is the AMD card actually being a smoother gaming experience. Turn the counter people like to put in the corner off and people will pick the AMD card. (I hope a few sites do the blind tests as they are both funny... and would be telling this gen)

 @alexandruciordas4941  The heck you going on about? A 3060Ti to a 9070 is an almost straight 60% performance boost most of the time at 1440p, not sure where you're getting 20% from. (actually I think i know and the sun don't shine there)
I went from a 3070 to a 9070 and seeing at least 50% stock performance boost and when i apply UV settings, I can get within the territory of the 9070XT for $100 less in actual real world pricing, while drawing less power, and not having to drop another extra $100 on a new PSU. 

The difference between a 3070 and 3060Ti on its own was in the 10-20% territory. Saying the 9070 is only a 20% bump from the 3060Ti, you're literally pulling numbers out your ass dude, get out of here with that.

 @alexandruciordas4941  it's been confirmed that you can flash the bios of a 9070 for the one on the 9070XT. They are made from the exact same die to start and the 9070 is a failed 9070xt with the cores cut or shutdown or their yields on the XT were so good that AMD still had to meet a 9070 quota and shut down the cores to make them. Both could've happened. Some old models of the RX480 with a 4GB and 8GB version was like this, where some of the 4GB models actually had the full 8GB, but was locked out due to the bios.

 tho it's not something I would attempt unless you have a card with a dual bios. Tho, if you have the capability to flash the bios of a gpu, then you probably already figured out how close you can already get to the 9070XT with UV and OC

Tldr: You're playing part of the Silicone Lottery. It'd result in a fancy overclock or you got a full 9070XT.

