is definitely the sweet spot for visual clarity and performance, and when you combine that with 1440p high refresh OLED, it’s the most immersive experience you can get for sure. I used to have the LG C2 as my OLED monitor, but since I’m a developer - the auto dimming protection was too aggressive when coding so it got too dim for me and I had move a window around aggressively to get the brightness back.. it got annoying so I landed on a 43” variant of the Samsung Odyssey G7 which is 144hz. Really not the best choice for purely gaming as the response times are kinda bad, but it’s decent for me - sure am missing the OLED experience though. 

I’m digressing - get a 1440p OLED and you won’t regret it :)

 @vaevictis2789 im not the guy but do you actually NOT think the MSRP is too high? You understand that last years cards were cutdown and marked up and not really the classes they were claiming to be? The 4070 and 4070 Ti should have been the 4060 Ti and 4070 with the 4080 supposed the be the 4070 Ti. Do you realize right now the 5070 is still slower than the 4070 Ti and and the 5070 Ti is still slightly slower than the 4080? The 5070 alone should be a 5050 Ti and the 5070 Ti should be the 5060. Of course its not that simple because they draw more power while being slightly faster, because blackwell is just Ada Lovelace with a power increase, thats why theyre barely faster.

Those cards even at MSRP are hilariously overpriced, let alone marked up or scalped. But AMD are putting out cards, that areonly barely better performance per value and tech wise are still worse.  This im gonna be honest, this gen from both companies is ass. Would I still recommend buying a 9070 or 9070 XT right now over an Nvidia counter part from 5000 series? Absolutely, but lets not glaze AMD and pretend they are looking out for gamers and not trying to scam us rotten while also needing improvement in a fair amount of things. The only thing i say good job to AMD for is for finally realizing upscaling isnt just a boxcheck and you need dedicated tech on board to do it with machine learning. Took them way too long but they finally narrowed the gap SUBSTANTIALLY between FSR and DLSS. Now they just have to work to make sure its as widely implemented.   

But, yes MSRP for the 9070 and 9070 XT is still too damn high, especially for AMD. They should be willing to lose money on these cards in order to build up SUBSTANTIAL mindshare while Nvidia directly tells gamers they hate them and dont need them and their new cards are falling apart. There is no reason right now for AMD to not out sell Nvidia by like 2 to 1 maybe even 3 to 1 this gen
